HOL-5: Styling with CSS Modules and Inline Styles

Need for styling react components

Styling makes components visually clear, organized, and easy to use
Well-structured components with consistent styling improve user experience
Different projects need different styling approaches depending on scale and reusability needs
Proper styling avoids messy, hard-to-maintain CSS across large applications
React supports several styling methods, each suited to different situations

CSS Modules

A CSS Module is a .module.css file where class names are scoped locally to the component
Prevents class name collisions between different components in the same app
Imported into a component using import styles from './File.module.css'
Applied using className={styles.className} syntax
Keeps styling modular, reusable, and conflict-free across a large codebase

Inline styles

Inline styles are written directly in JSX using the style attribute
The value must be a JavaScript object, with camelCase property names (e.g., backgroundColor)
Useful for dynamic styles that depend on data, like changing text color based on status
Do not require a separate CSS file, but are less reusable than CSS Modules
In this hands-on, inline styles were used to change <h3> color based on cohort status

Applying styles using className and style properties

className links JSX elements to CSS classes defined in a stylesheet or CSS Module
style applies styles directly as an object, calculated at runtime if needed
Both can be used together in the same component for different purposes
className is best for static, reusable styles; style is best for dynamic, conditional styles
This hands-on combined both: className for the card layout, style for conditional heading color
